Univariate Plots Section

Lets take a look at each of the variable histograms

It appears that density and pH are normally distributed, with few outliers.

Fixed and volatile acidity, sulfur dioxides, sulphates, and alcohol seem to be long-tailed.

It seems, residual sugar, chlorides, density have extreme outliers.

Lets take a closer look at each of the variables below.

Quality

## 
##    3    4    5    6    7    8    9 
##   20  163 1457 2198  880  175    5

Here we can see quality ranges from 3 - 9, we don’t have much data (if any) for exceptionally good or bad wines.

Given the ratings and distribution of wine quality, I’ll create another categorical variable, classifying the wines as ‘bad’ (rating 0 to 4), ‘average’ (rating 5 - 7), and ‘excellent’ (rating 8 to 9). By splitting the data this way we have roughly the same amount of wines in our bad and excellent categories.

wine$rating <- ifelse(wine$quality < 5, 'bad', ifelse(
  wine$quality < 8, 'average', 'excellent'))

wine$rating <- ordered(wine$rating,
                     levels = c('bad', 'average', 'excellent'))

summary(wine$rating)
##       bad   average excellent 
##       183      4535       180

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

My dataset is related to the quality of white wine. The dataset is already tidy with observation mentioning the chemical physicochemical of the wine. There are 4898 observations of 13 variables. The variable ‘quality’ is based on the median rating by 3 wine experts. The other physicochemical variables are fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates and alcohol.

The quality variable can be seen as factor variable with 0 to 10 i.e. 11 possible levels, where only 7 levels are present in dataset i.e . 3-9.

It’s important to note that only physicochemical variables are available, there is no data on other variables such as grape type, wine brand, wine selling price etc.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I’m interested to see if any of the variables produce consistently good, or bad white wine.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Binned values in the quality column, providing me with a range of bad, average and excellent wines. I also created a variable to highlight if free bound SO2 levels were noticeable in the wine or not.

Bivariate Plots Section

Lets examine the corrolation matrix

Key factors that seem to have correlation with quality of wine are density and alcohol.

I’m also going to examine the corolations between density and residual sugar and the relationship between sulfur dioxides.

pH is also negatively corrolated with fixed acidity, I feel like this is obvious and doesn’t need investigating much further.

Density

Lets look at the two highest correlating variables with density. It looks like density is correlated negatively alcohol, and positively with residual sugar amounts. I think intuitively this should be correct as more sugar would result in an increase in density, and vice versa for alcohol amounts.

Citric Acid

I noticed a peak at 0.49g / l, I’m going to see if these wines had any higher quality then all other wines. Perhaps this is the sweet spot for a fresh tasting wine?

wine %>% group_by(citric.acid == 0.49) %>%
    summarise(mean(quality), count = n())

Alcohol

Now I’m going to look at the variables that could have an impact on quality. It seems like the relationship between alcohol and rating is not lineraly positive, leading to higher scoring wines generally having a higher alcohol content.
The mean alcohol content for excellent wines was 11.6%, whereas bad quality wines had an average content of 10.2%.

Multivariate Plots Section

Free sulphur

According to our correlation plot - free sulfur and quality are not correlated. Perhaps the if we take a look at noticeable amounts of free sulfur they can correlate with quality levels. Next up I compared the total sulfur to quality correlations.

## [1] "Full wine quality/ sulfur correlation: 0.0082"
## [1] "Not noticable sulfur / quality correlation: -0.1263"
## [1] "Noteiceable sulfur / quality correlation: -0.2935"

So when we have a noticeable amount of sulfur in the wine there is a stronger negative correlation between total sulfur and quality.

Total SO2 content is made up of free and bound sulfur content, it’s interesting to see how some wines have a higher total sulfur content but it is still not noticeable as I assume free sulfur dioxide levels remain below 50.

Lets explore how the noticeable free sulfur dioxide levels relate to alcohol and quality.

It seems almost consistently wines with not noticeable sulfur levels have a higher alcohol content. A higher alcohol content is a key variable in leading to the quality of wine. Therefore if you’re looking to avoid sulfur, pick a wine with a higher alcohol content!

Alcohol vs Volatile Acidity

We know wines with a higher alcohol percentage and lower acetic acid level tend to be a higher quality. Lets visualise this by looking at the “bad” and “excellent” wines in our data.

Straight away we can see that this holds true, most of our higher quality wines are in the bottom right of the graph showing they have a higher alcohol content and lower acetic acid level.

Multivariate Analysis

Three key relationships were discovered here, firstly we looked at how the levels of SO2 in wine can have different total amounts yet still be undectable due to unnoticeable levels of SO2. Once SO2 levels were noticeabel there is a slight correlation between total SO2 levels and quality.

Next, we explored how white wines with a higher alcohol content generally have a lower level of total SO2.

Finally we explored two characteristics in white wine and how that higher quality white wines generally have lower volitile acid levels as well as a higher alcohol percentage.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot one

Description One

The first final plot I’ve chosen highlights the distribution of wines within the dataset. It’s important to not there was not a balanced distribution of bad, excellent and average wines. This begs the question, is this the distribution for wines generally, or just for this dataset? The data also contained no entries for wines have a score of 1, 2 or 10 - I can see how this is possible as quality scores are defined as the mean from 3 expert opinions, making it difficult to achieve these scores.

Plot Two

Description Two

My next plot shows how a characteristic of excellent wine is having a higher alcohol percentage. This was the strongest correlation I found within my data of 0.44, however this is not particularly strong so should not be used as the primary indicator in white wine quality.

Plot Three

Description Three

During the multivariant analysis I discovered that higher quality wines tended to have a higher alcohol content as well as a lower volatile acidity content. It’s possible that his has a synergistic effect on the taste of the wine as a higher alcohol percentage could also mask the acidity taste from wine.

Reflection

I feel that wine quality is decided by many independent factors, it is very difficult to distinguish wine quality just by combinding of two factors. Also, a large number of factors were not present in this data that could have accounted for a change in quality such as wine price, brand or grape type. This dataset had limited data on excellent and poorer qualities of wines, making it difficult to produce a representative analysis. Findings from this analysis can only be generalised to the Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine, it’s very likely that different types of white wine will have varyingly different factors that conttribute towards quality.
